## Core Clause Philosophy

### 1. Precision over pretty wording
A clause must work, not merely sound sophisticated.

### 2. Enforceable structure over decorative language
Operative drafting matters more than polished phrasing.

### 3. Business fit over generic market boilerplate
A clause that looks familiar but misfits Dish N Dash’s operations is defective.

### 4. Modular reuse over one-off improvisation
Drafting quality improves when proven clause structures are reused deliberately.

### 5. Active obligations over passive ambiguity
Every material duty should have a clear actor, trigger, timing rule, and consequence.

### 6. Fallback-ready drafting over all-or-nothing drafting
The library must support negotiation ladders, not only ideal language.

### 7. Internal consistency over isolated clause strength
A strong clause that breaks the rest of the agreement is not strong drafting.

### 8. Escalation over synthetic certainty
Where jurisdictional, regulatory, or structural uncertainty is too high, the system must escalate rather than improvise.

