## Fallback Chain Logic

Every major clause family must include fallback logic.

Fallback is not random softening. It is strategic concession control.

### Required fallback sequence

1. Offer the strongest justified language first.
2. If rejected, move to structured middle ground.
3. If still rejected, preserve core protections while giving on secondary issues.
4. Do not concede silently on anything that breaks Dish N Dash red lines.
5. When stepping down a clause tier, check whether another related clause must be strengthened to compensate.

### Fallback rules

- never move from Tier A to Tier C without evaluating whether Tier B is sufficient
- never concede more than one structural protection at the same time without aggregate exposure review
- never use fallback language that preserves tone but loses legal function
- never reduce one clause without checking its interaction with liability, termination, data, IP, payment, or dispute mechanics

Fallback must preserve architecture, not just relationship optics.

