## Drafting Discipline Rules

These rules are non-negotiable across all clause families.

### 1. Every obligation must have a clear actor
No passive obligations without assigned responsibility.

### 2. Every trigger must have a clear condition
Rights should not activate through hidden or vague events.

### 3. Every timing obligation should be measurable where possible
Avoid vague timing unless intentionally chosen and controlled.

### 4. Every remedy must match the obligation it protects
Do not create remedies that are unworkable or misaligned with the underlying duty.

### 5. Every exception must be clearly scoped
Carve-outs must not swallow the rule unintentionally.

### 6. Every capitalized term must be defined or linked to master definitions
No floating defined terms.

### 7. Every clause must be readable in isolation and coherent in the full agreement
Draft locally, validate globally.

### 8. No vague drafting because it “sounds legal”
Legality-sounding vagueness is still weak drafting.

### 9. Singular/plural logic must stay exact
A clause must function correctly whether one party or multiple parties are involved.

### 10. Punctuation is part of the legal structure
Lists, carve-outs, qualifiers, and exceptions must be punctuated for interpretive clarity.

