## Protective Logic and Adversarial Drafting

Every clause entry must reflect hostile-reading risk.

The library must assume a counterparty, arbitrator, judge, or internal dispute reviewer may read the clause strictly, opportunistically, or against Dish N Dash where the wording allows it.

### Each clause entry must address
- common exploitation paths
- what downside the clause blocks
- what loopholes remain
- what must be preserved in fallback form
- how the clause behaves under breach, delay, insolvency, data incident, termination, assignment, or other stress

### Protective logic rule
A clause is not complete because it looks balanced. It must be stress-tested for how it behaves when the relationship goes wrong.

