## Clause Family Guidance

The following section defines how the main clause families should be handled in this library.

### Definitions
Definitions must be narrow enough to control risk and broad enough to capture intended scope. They must never be decorative. High-priority definitions often control the entire risk profile.

### Scope of Services / Deliverables
This family must state what is actually being provided, what is excluded, what dependencies exist, what assumptions apply, and how changes are handled.

### Payment Terms
This family must define timing, invoicing, settlement mechanics, withholding, disputes, default consequences, credits, and any fee dependencies.

### Fees, Commissions, and Pricing Adjustments
This family must be formula-safe. It must define base amounts, calculation methods, excluded amounts, reporting dependencies, audit support where needed, and adjustment triggers.

### Confidentiality
This family must define scope, permitted use, permitted disclosures, security expectations, survival period, return/destruction mechanics, and carve-outs carefully.

### Data Protection / Data Use
This family must separate ownership, access, permitted use, restrictions, deletion/return obligations, analytics rights, aggregation rights, and security obligations clearly.

### IP Ownership
This family must define who owns pre-existing IP, newly created IP, feedback, derivative outputs, and branded materials. It must be drafted with funding, product, and platform realities in mind.

### License Grants
This family must define scope, purpose, exclusivity, territory, sublicensing, transfer rights, revocation, and survival interaction.

### Warranties and Disclaimers
This family must match the actual service and risk profile. It should not create promises Dish N Dash cannot perform or accept disclaimers that destroy the commercial purpose.

### Indemnities
This family must define who indemnifies whom, for what categories of claims, under what procedures, with what exclusions, and how indemnity interacts with liability caps.

### Limitation of Liability
This family must define cap structure, excluded damages, cap carve-outs, and alignment with indemnity and confidentiality obligations.

### Term and Termination
This family must define term mechanics, renewal logic, termination triggers, cure periods, post-termination duties, payment consequences, data return/destruction, and transition support where necessary.

### Termination for Convenience / Cause
This family must distinguish voluntary exit from breach-based exit and ensure operational consequences are handled clearly.

### Notice
This family must define delivery methods, deemed receipt, addresses, and interaction with time-sensitive rights.

### Assignment / Change of Control
This family must control transfer risk, especially where counterparty identity matters operationally, commercially, or strategically.

### Exclusivity / Non-Compete Sensitivity
This family must be treated cautiously. It should clearly define scope, duration, territory, and prohibited conduct, and should escalate where risk is strategically significant.

### Audit Rights
This family must define who can audit what, when, how often, under what confidentiality constraints, and at whose cost.

### Service Levels / Support
This family must define measurable service obligations, exclusions, reporting, credits or remedies, and operational realism.

### Force Majeure
This family must define qualifying events, notice obligations, mitigation, suspension consequences, and termination rights if disruption continues.

### Governing Law / Dispute Resolution
This family must align with actual deal reality, notice mechanics, interim relief needs, and escalation posture.

### Compliance with Laws
This family must be specific enough to matter and not so broad that it creates hidden absolute obligations disconnected from the relationship.

### Publicity / Use of Name and Marks
This family must control announcement rights, logo use, case-study rights, approval mechanics, and brand misuse risk.

### Survival
This family must state what survives and avoid accidental survival gaps or overbroad survival that creates lingering obligations beyond business need.

### Entire Agreement / Amendment / Waiver
This family must preserve integration discipline and avoid informal amendment drift where the relationship is operationally complex.

### Relationship of Parties
This family must clarify independent contractor status or other intended relationship structure without misdescribing actual operational obligations.

