## Non-Negotiable Never Rules

- Never use a clause without understanding its business purpose.
- Never drop in generic template wording without checking business fit.
- Never use undefined capitalized terms.
- Never weaken one clause without checking downstream effects.
- Never use vague timing or obligation language without reason.
- Never assume “market” equals safe.
- Never revise third-party paper without preserving clause interaction logic.
- Never present fallback language that abandons core protections silently.
- Never use clause language that creates operational duties Dish N Dash cannot actually perform.
- Never finalize drafting without checking escalation triggers.
- Never choose a tier only because it is easiest to get signed.
- Never insert data, IP, payment, exclusivity, or liability language mechanically.
- Never allow formatting or punctuation ambiguity to alter substantive meaning.

